ly and self-consciously writerly form of his work. Critiquing the categorization of Miller into specific literary genres through an examination of the small body of critical texts on his oeuvre, Masuga draws on Deleuze and Guattari's concept of a minor literature, Blanchot's "infinite curve," and Bataille's theory of puerile language, while also considering Miller in relation to other writers, including Proust, Rilke, and William Carlos Williams. She shows how Miller defies conventional modes of writing, subverting language from within. Katy Masuga is Adjunct Professor of British and American literature, cinema, and the arts in the Cultural Studies Department at the University of Paris III: Sorbonne Nouvelle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aExplicit.  aFiction.  aHenry Miller.  aLanguage.  aObscenity.  aSelf-critique.  aSelf-reflection.  aSexuality.  aWriting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781571137647?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571137647423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571137647/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles